(LS-R2L) method that uses the local search for rewiring of edges guided by the objective function Eq. (11). At each step, we search the local neighborhood for a set of possible solutions that improve the objective value, and move to that solution. The local search is performed at lines 5–8 by rewiring a subset of edges and the effect of each change is calculated. Then at line 12, a solution is picked with probability proportional to the improvement in objective values. These steps are repeated until a local minimum is reached or the maximum number of steps T is reached.

We also like to discuss two more approaches based on random rewiring heuristics that provide better model averaging behavior than RRL, but are interestingly not employed in decentralized SGD. The first solution is proposed by Watts and Strogatz [17] to construct a small-world graph. They proposed a mechanism of converting an RRL to a small-world graph, by rewiring edges based on a given probability \documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
